The Centre for the Protection of Rights of the Citizen (CPRC) has faulted the Peoples Democratic Party (PDP) for crying wolf over the decision of the supreme court to reserve its judgement in Zamfara state. A statement made available to LEADERSHIP yesterday in Abuja, signed by national coordinator, Muhammad Ahmad, said it observed that it was in the character of the PDP to always cry foul each time the decision of the court was not in its favour. It said the apex court deserves more respect from Nigerians and in particular the Peoples Democratic Party (PDP). CPRC also reminded the PDP that the court was not in any way obligated to do the bidding of the party but to serve justice to all irrespective of party affiliation, religion or ethnicity. The statement said that over the years, the supreme court being the highest court of the land has proven itself beyond reasonable doubt in its tenacity to serve as the last hope for the common man. “Without prejudice, we like to remind the whole world that the Zamfara governorship tussles was purely an intra party matter of which PDP was not a party to the litigation and because it was a case involving governorship primary election only, we are hopeful that the consequential order earlier issued in favor of the PDP would be set aside in the interest of justice. “The Peoples Democratic Party should understand that it has no right whatsoever to dictate to the supreme court and as such, we urge the apex court to take its time and study the appeal before delivering its judgement. “Let us henceforth allay the fears of the general public and as well urge them to ignore every rumour peddled by the PDP of plots to manipulate the judicial process so as to secure judgment through the back door.”